Looked up some info on the Guennol Lioness and:
>Many ancient Near East deities were represented in anthropomorphic figures. Such images evoked the Mesopotamian belief in attaining power over the physical world by combining the superior physical attributes of various species. It is possible that the nearby Sumerians borrowed this powerful artistic hybrid from the Proto-Elamites. The lioness was the frequent subject of veneration among cultures with exposure to the characteristic hunting techniques of the species that feature well-coordinated hunting by its female members.

Given how anthropomorphic animal deities, people and entites existed in so many cultures over so many different eras and have evolved independently, I'm starting to think that making waifurs reality is actually the endgame of mankind. Anonymous Sat 13 Feb 2021 16:07:38 No.36300753 Report
Quoted By: >>36300946
>>36300649
When you draw be sure to have a plan of what the finished drawing is supposed to look like roughly. Don't just put lines on paper and decide afterwards what they are going to be. I'm not trying to be condescending here, but that is a big problem a lot of people have when starting out drawing. Being able to visualize what you are going to do before even putting down your first line is a key skill and unfortunately takes a lot of time and effort to internalize.
Something that I started doing when I realized that for myself was to force myself to draw with an ink or ballpoint pen. Once a line has been drawn it's there and will never go away. For me that was a very helpful exercise to get better at drawing.

Keep in mind that this advice may not help you in any way, since drawing is an abstract and ethereal craft which has problems to which there are many different answers that are completely different, but all correct. When you learn to draw you have to try as much as possible and stick with the stuff that works for you

Anonymous Sat 13 Feb 2021 16:38:13 No.36301141 Report
Quoted By: >>36301416
>>36300946
No problem, learning to draw is a noble endeavor. /trash/ has a general dedicated to improving one's drawing and you could go to /ic/ and at least read the sticky.

And to answer the actual questions you asked: You can become a very good artist barely spending anything. I recently bought 0.7mm mechanical pencil with 2B (soft) leads, works great. A pair of 2B and HB pencils should be enough for starters and I had no issue with drawing on cheap printer paper, just make sure you use the slightly rougher side to draw on. Something that I would highly recommend is a lightboard to backlight your paper (dealing with the shadow of your hand can be a pain in the ass) and especially a table easel or drawing stand like pic related. I bought one just like that for like 25 bucks, best purchase I have ever made for drawing. You can keep your paper perfectly perpendicular to your eye (avoiding distortion when looking at the paper at an angle) without fucking up your back.

Yeah bro just give em a couple hundred million years to get rid of their primary advantage. Even if some species develop hyper intelligence or outright sapience it won't do them any good to develop civilizations or tool use if their bodies aren't suited for tool use (i.e. dolphins and birds).

Raccoons are almost certainly in the best position to take up the place of humans outside of the other primates. Even then they have poor enough cooperation to make it still seriously up for debate.

Anonymous Sun 14 Feb 2021 02:50:20 No.36314081 Report
Quoted By: >>36314209 >>36314675
>>36313150
Start with the defining character change at the end of the story, The self revelation. In a love story where your mc gets with the gal, your character self revelation has them taking an action that gets them the gal that they otherwise would never take. This is because they have a weakness that is hurting others. They justify that weakness with ideals or values. You can have your character bring up said ideals for them to justify themselves wenever they hurt someone and are criticized by someone who they actually care about, an ally.
A conflict occurs because people desire the same thing. Since your characters have values, whoever wins the conflict demonstrates as having superior values. Of course earlier we said our hero has weaknesses that are hurting others. They and their opponent can both have wrong values. But the hero in battle can change and then take the right action (and thus represent the right values) to defeat the antag.
All of this off the top of my head from John Trubys 22 steps. If you want a pdf just ask.
